licquy, Hainaut, Belgique":"Blicquy, Henegouwen, België","Europe":"Europa","Holy Roman Empire":"Heiliges Römisches Reich"},"en":{"1092–1136":"1092–1136","1095–1138":"1095–1138","1118–1161":"1118–1161","1135–Female":"1135–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1070–1126":"1070–1126","1075–1136":"1075–1136","1090":"1090","1075":"1075","1161":"1161","1095":"1095","1092":"1092","1070":"1070","1118":"1118","1138":"1138","1126":"1126","1136":"1136","1135":"1135","about 1113":"about 1113","about 1135":"about 1135","Trazegnies, Courcelles, Hainaut, Belgium":"Trazegnies, Courcelles, Hainaut, Belgium","Blicquy, Hainaut, Belgique":"Blicquy, Hainaut, Belgium","Europe":"Europe","Holy Roman Empire":"Holy Roman Empire","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"DE","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Otton","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a short form of any of the various Germanic compound personal names containing the element <i>od</i>, <i>ot</i> ‘prosperity, wealth’ (  compare the corresponding Old English <i>ēad</i> in names such as  Edward   and   Edwin  ).  St Otto of Bamberg  (  d. 1139 ) was a missionary to the Pomeranians.  Otto the Great  (  912–73 ) is generally regarded as the founder of the Holy Roman Empire, and the name has been borne by several members of German and Austrian royal houses. It was recorded occasionally among immigrants to England from the Low Countries in the 14th century, but failed to establish itself. Since the 19th century it has again been used occasionally in the English-speaking world, mostly among immigrants from Germanic countries."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from Yiddish <i>ber</i> ‘bear’, probably influenced by the early medieval European practice of giving animal names to people. It is often paired with   Dov   in order to provide a Hebrew name in certain rituals."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Otton Ier DE TRAZEGNIES DE FLEMALLE was born in 1092, in Trazegnies, Courcelles, Hainaut, Belgium, his father, Gilles De Silly De Trazégnies, was 23 and his mother, Beatrice d'Ath, was 17. He married Helvide DE SILLY DE REVES about 1113, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1136, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1092–1136":"1092–1136","1095–1138":"1095–1138","1118–1161":"1118–1161","1135–Female":"1135–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1070–1126":"1070–1126","1075–1136":"1075–1136","1090":"1090","1075":"1075","1161":"1161","1095":"1095","1092":"1092","1070"